ght;\" | + 3h 19' 33\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 45\n| {{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Le Grev\u00e8s]]|FRA}}||West || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 3h 35' 53\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 46\n| {{flagathlete|[[Janus Hellemons]]|NED}}||Netherlands || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 3h 44' 16\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 47\n| {{flagathlete|[[Am\u00e9d\u00e9e Fournier]]|FRA}}||Ile de France/North East || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 4h 01' 56\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 48\n| {{flagathlete|[[Joseph Soffietti]]|FRA}}||South-East || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 4h 18' 46\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 49\n| {{flagathlete|[[Armand Le Moal]]|FRA}}||West || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 4h 26' 39\"\n|}\n\n===Mountains classification===\n\n{{columns-start}}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Mountains in the mountains classification<ref name=\"mdc1939\"/>{{sfn|Augendre|2016|pp=175\u2013192}}\n|-\n!Stage!! scope=\"col\" | Rider!!Height!!Mountain range!! scope=\"col\" | Winner\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 9\n|Aubisque||{{convert|1709|m|ft}}||Pyrenees||Edward Vissers\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 9\n|Tourmalet||{{convert|2115|m|ft}}||Pyrenees||Edward Vissers\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 9\n|Aspin||{{convert|1489|m|ft}}||Pyrenees||Edward Vissers\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 13\n|Braus||{{convert|1002|m|ft}}||Alps-Maritimes||Sylv\u00e8re Maes\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 15\n|Allos||{{convert|2250|m|ft}}||Alps||Edward Vissers\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 15\n|Vars||{{convert|2110|m|ft}}||Alps||Edward Vissers\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 15\n|Izoard||{{convert|2361|m|ft}}||Alps||Sylv\u00e8re Maes\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 16a\n|Galibier||{{convert|2556|m|ft}}||Alps||Dante Gianello\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 16\n|Iseran||{{convert|2770|m|ft}}||Alps||Sylv\u00e8re Maes\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 17a\n|Faucille||{{convert|1320|m|ft}}||Alps||Sylv\u00e8re Maes\n|}\n\n{{column}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Final mountains classification (1\u20135)<ref name=\"mdc1939\"/><ref name=\"tgv\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tour-giro-vuelta.net/|title=Tour-Giro-Vuelta|accessdate=14 October 2009|author=Van Lonkhuyzen, Michiel}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Rank!! scope=\"col\" | Rider!! scope=\"col\" | Team!! scope=\"col\" | Points\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |1\n| {{flagathlete|[[Sylv\u00e8re Maes]]|BEL}}||Belgium|| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 86\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |2\n| {{flagathlete|[[Edward Vissers]]|BEL}}||Belgium|| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 84\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |3\n| {{flagathlete|[[Albert Ritseveldt]]|BEL}}||Belgium B|| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 71\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |4\n| {{flagathlete|[[Dante Gianello]]|FRA}}||France|| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 61\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |5\n| {{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Vietto]]|FRA}} ||South-East|| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 22\n|}\n\n{{columns-end}}\n\n===Team classification===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Final team classification (1\u20139)<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/><ref name=\"lc\">{{cite news|url=http://www.archiefleeuwardercourant.nl/site/article.do?code=LC&date=19390731&id=LC-19390731-11007|title=De Ronde van Frankrijk \u2013 Sylver Maes winnaar|date=31 July 1939|accessdate=14 October 2009|publisher=Leeuwarder Courant|language=Dutch}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Rank!! scope=\"col\" | Team!! scope=\"col\" | Time\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |1\n| Belgium B || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 398h 17' 20\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |2\n| France || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 35' 47\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |3\n| Belgium || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 36' 18\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |4\n| Luxembourg || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 1h 12' 35\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |5\n| France North-East || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 1h 23' 20\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |6\n| France South-East || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 1h 38' 09\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |7\n| Netherlands || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 2h 06' 07\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |8\n| France West || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 5h 50' 37\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |9\n| Switzerland || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 6h 45' 27\"\n|}\n\n==Aftermath==\nAlthough he did not win the race, Ren\u00e9 Vietto became a popular cyclist. He was the most popular runner-up in France until [[Raymond Poulidor]].<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/>\n\nThe sales of the organising newspaper ''[[l'Auto]]'' had dropped to 164000, and the newspaper was sold to [[Raymond Paten\u00f4tre]].{{sfn|Thompson|2008|p=310}} A few months after Germany had conquered France in the Second World War, Paten\u00f4tre sold l'Auto to the Germans.{{sfn|Thompson|2008|p=35}}\n\nDirectly after the Tour, the organisation announced the 1940 Tour de France would be run in 20 stages and five rest days.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://emeroteca.coni.it/?q=node/6&f=3804&p=1|title=Novita per l'edizione 1940|work=Il littoriale|publisher=Biblioteca digitale|language=Italian|date=31 July 1939|accessdate=11 February 2010}}</ref> But the Second World War made it impossible to hold a Tour de France in the next years, although [[Tour de France during the Second World War|some replacing races]] were held. Only in 1947 would the Tour be held again, and Vietto would again play an important role then, holding the yellow jersey as leader of the general classification for 15 of the 21 stages.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://veloarchive.com/races/tour/1947.php|title=1947: Robic snatches it at the death|author=James, Tom|date=15 August 2003|accessdate=25 January 2010|publisher=VeloArchive}}</ref>\n\nThe victory of Maes would be the last Belgian Tour victory for 30 years, until [[Eddy Merckx]] won the [[1969 Tour de France]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.standaard.be/artikel/detail.aspx?artikelid=DMF20090721_001|title=21 juli 1969. Eddy Merckx wint zijn eerste Tour|date=21 July 2009|publisher=De Standaard|language=Dutch|accessdate=25 January 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book|first=Jacques|last=Augendre|author-link=Jacques Augendre|url=http://netstorage.lequipe.fr/ASO/cyclisme/le-tour/2016/histoire/TDF16_GH_Interactif-PROD.pdf|title=Guide historique|trans-title=Historical guide|year=2016|language=French|access-date=27 October 2016|format=PDF|work=[[Tour de France]]|location=Paris|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817121602/http://netstorage.lequipe.fr/ASO/cyclisme/le-tour/2016/histoire/TDF16_GH_Interactif-PROD.pdf|archive-date=17 August 2016|url-status=live|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Bowen|first=Wayne H|url=https://archive.org/details/spainduringworld00bowe_0|url-access=registration|title=Spain During World War II|location=Columbia, MO|publisher=[[University of Missouri Press]]|year=2006|isbn=978-0-8262-1658-8|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=McGann|first1=Bill|last2=McGann|first2=Carol|title=The Story of the Tour de France: 1903\u20131964|volume=1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jxq20JskqMUC|publisher=Dog Ear Publishing|location=Indianapolis, IN|year=2006|isbn=978-1-59858-180-5|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Nauright|first1=John|last2=Parrish|first2=Charles|title=Sports Around the World: History, Culture, and Practice|volume=2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IkLYDgTnMxEC|year=2012|publisher=[[ABC-CLIO]]|location=Santa Barbara, CA|isbn=978-1-59884-300-2|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Thompson|first=Christopher S.|title=The Tour de France: A Cultural History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UpzzPqexF00C|publisher=[[University of California Press]]|location=Oakland, CA|year=2008|isbn=978-0-520-25630-9|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline|Tour de France 1939|1939 Tour de France}}\n\n{{Cycling stage recaps|1939 Tour de France|1|10c|11|18b}}\n{{Tour de France}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1939 Tour De France}}\n[[Category:1939 Tour de France| ]]\n[[Category:1939 in road cycling|Tour de France]]\n[[Category:Tour de France by year]]\n[[Category:July 1939 sports events|Tour de France]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox cycling race report\n| name               = 1939 Tour de France\n| image              = Tour de France 1939.png\n| image_caption      = Route of the 1939 Tour de France followed counterclockwise, starting in Paris\n| image_alt          = \n| image_size         = 300px\n| date               = 10\u201330 July\n| stages             = 18, including eight split stages\n| distance           = 4224\n| unit               = km\n| time               = 132h 03' 17\"\n| first              = [[Sylv\u00e8re Maes]]\n| first_nat          = BEL\n| first_color        = yellow\n| first_team         = Belgium\n| second             = [[Ren\u00e9 Vietto]]\n| second_nat         = FRA\n| second_team        = France\n| third              = [[Lucien Vlaemynck]]\n| third_nat          = BEL\n| third_team         = Belgium B\n| team               = Belgium B\n| mountains          = [[Sylv\u00e8re Maes]]\n| mountains_nat      = BEL\n| mountains_team     = Belgium\n| previous           = [[1938 Tour de France|1938]]\n| next               = [[1947 Tour de France|1947]]\n}}\nThe '''1939 Tour de France''' was the 33rd edition of the [[Tour de France]], taking place from 10 to 30 July. The total distance was {{convert|4224|km|0|abbr=on}}.\n\nTaking place on the eve of [[World War II]], there was already much animosity in Europe. Italy, Germany and Spain all declined to send teams to the race, so the [[1938 Tour de France|1938]] Italian champion [[Gino Bartali]] would not be defending his title.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://enenvor.fr/eeo_revue/numero_2/velo/du_cliquetis_des_p%C3%A9dales_au_bruit_des_bottes.pdf|title=Du cliquetis des p\u00e9dales au bruit des bottes : un \u00e9t\u00e9 cycliste perturb\u00e9 en Bretagne (juillet-septembre 1939)|format=PDF|last=Evanno|first=Yves-Marie|publisher=En Envor, revue d'histoire contemporaine en Bretagne|year=2013|accessdate=16 December 2013|language=French|archiveurl=http://enenvor.fr/eeo_revue/numero_2/du_cliquetis_des_pedales_au_bruit_des_bottes.html|archivedate=1 June 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> To fill out the ranks, Belgium sent two teams, and France had five teams. This would be the final Tour for eight years, until [[1947 Tour de France|1947]].\n\nBetween the second and the seventh stage, the last rider in the general classification was eliminated.<ref name=\"mdc1939\"/>\n\nThe race was won by Belgian [[Sylv\u00e8re Maes]] who also won the mountains classification.\n\n==Changes from the previous Tour==\nFor the first time, a mountain time trial was scheduled: stage 16b.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=144\u2013147}}\nA rule was added to make it more difficult to finish the race: from the second stage to the seventh stage, the last rider in the classification was to be removed from the race.<ref name=\"mdc1939\"/>\n\nThe nutrition of the cyclists became more professional: cyclists were reporting that the use of vitamins increased their performance.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Applegate |first1=Elizabeth A.  |last2=Grivetti |first2=Louis E. |year= 1997 |title=Search for the Competitive Edge: A History of Dietary Fads and Supplements |journal=The Journal of Nutrition |volume=127|pmid=9164254 |issue=5 |pages=869S\u2013873S |url=http://jn.nutrition.org/cgi/content/full/127/5/869S |doi= }}</ref>\n\n==Teams==\n{{main list|List of teams and cyclists in the 1939 Tour de France}}\n\nBecause Italy, Germany and Spain did not send teams,{{sfn|Bowen|2006|p=152}} the Tour organisation were short on participating cyclists. To solve this, they allowed Belgium to send two teams, and France to send four additional regional teams.<ref name=\"veloarchive\">{{cite web|url=http://veloarchive.com/races/tour/1939.php|title=1939: \"Le Roi Ren\u00e9\" and the regionals|author=James, Tom|date=15 August 2003|accessdate=25 January 2010|publisher=VeloArchive}}</ref>\n\nThe French cyclists had been successful in the 1930s, but their Tour winners were absent in 1939:\n1930 and 1932 winner [[Andr\u00e9 Leducq]] had retired in 1938, as had 1931 and 1934 winner [[Antonin Magne]]; 1933 winner [[Georges Speicher]] did not ride, and 1937 winner [[Roger Lap\u00e9bie]] was injured. This all made the Belgian team favourite.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=144\u2013147}}\n\nThe teams entering the race were:\n\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* Belgium\n* Switzerland\n* Luxembourg\n* Netherlands\n* France\n* Belgium B\n* France North-East/\u00cele de France\n* France West\n* France South-West\n* France South-East\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Route and stages==\n\nThe [[List of highest points reached in the Tour de France|highest point of elevation in the race]] was {{convert|2770|m|ft|abbr=on}} at the summit of the [[Col de l'Iseran]] mountain pass on stage 16b.{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=178}}<ref>{{cite news|title=Et voici, dix ans apres... Le Tour de France 1939|trans-title=And here, ten years later... The Tour de France 1939|url=https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k97984033/f3.item|work=[[:fr:Le Miroir des sports|Le Miroir des sports]]|date=11 July 1939|page=3|language=French|via=[[Gallica]]}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Stage characteristics and winners<ref name=\"mdc1939\">{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1939.php|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306131903/http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1939.php|archive-date=6 March 2012|access-date=28 October 2016|url-status=dead|publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme|title=33\u00e8me Tour de France 1939|language=French}}</ref>{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=37}}<ref name=\"topten\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cvccbike.com/tour/top_ten.html#1939 |title=Tour de France GC top ten |first=Arian |last=Zwegers |publisher=CVCC |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080516071832/http://www.cvccbike.com/tour/top_ten.html |archivedate=16 May 2008 |url-status=live |accessdate=20 April 2009  }}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Stage\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | Course\n! scope=\"col\" | Distance\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\" | Type{{efn|The icons shown here indicate whether the stage was run as a time trial, the stage was flat or the stage included mountains for the mountains classification. Stage 16b was a time trial that included a mountain.}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Winner\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1939 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 10c#Stage 1|1]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |10 July|| [[Paris]] to [[Caen]] || {{convert|215|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Am\u00e9d\u00e9e Fournier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1939 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 10c#Stage 2a|2a]]\n|rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\" |11 July|| [[Caen]] to [[Vire]] || {{convert|64|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Time Trial.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || [[Individual time trial]] || {{flagathlete|[[Romain Maes]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1939 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 10c#Stage 2b|2b]]\n| [[Vire]] to [[Rennes]] || {{convert|119|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[\u00c9loi Tassin]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1939 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 10c#Stage 3|3]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |12 July|| [[Rennes]] to [[Brest, France|Brest]]|| {{convert|244|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Pierre Cloarec]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1939 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 10c#Stage 4|4]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |13 July|| [[Brest Region|Brest]] to [[Lorient]] || {{convert|174|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Raymond Louviot]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1939 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 10c#Stage 5|5]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |14 July|| [[Lorient]] to [[Nantes]] || {{convert|207|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Am\u00e9d\u00e9e Fournier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1939 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 10c#Stage 6a|6a]]\n|rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\" |15 July|| [[Nantes]] to [[La Rochelle]] || {{convert|144|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Lucien Storme]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1939 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 10c#Stage 6b|6b]]\n| [[La Rochelle]] to [[Royan]] || {{convert|107|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Edmond Pag\u00e8s]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 16 July\n| colspan=\"2\" | [[Royan]]\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" | Rest day\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1939 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 10c#Stage 7|7]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |17 July|| [[Royan]] to [[Bordeaux]] || {{convert|198|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Raymond Passat]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1939 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 10c#Stage 8a|8a]]\n|rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\" |18 July|| [[Bordeaux]] to [[Salies-de-B\u00e9arn]] || {{convert|210|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Marcel Kint]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1939 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 10c#Stage 8b|8b]]\n| [[Salies-de-B\u00e9arn]] to [[Pau, Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques|Pau]] || {{convert|69|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Time Trial.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || [[Individual time trial]] || {{flagathlete|[[Karl Litschi]]|SUI}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1939 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 10c#Stage 9|9]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |19 July|| [[Pau, Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques|Pau]] to [[Toulouse]] || {{convert|311|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s) || {{flagathlete|[[Edward Vissers]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 20 July\n| colspan=\"2\" | [[Toulouse]]\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" | Rest day\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1939 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 10c#Stage 10a|10a]]\n|rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\" |21 July|| [[Toulouse]] to [[Narbonne]] || {{convert|149|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Pierre Jaminet]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1939 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 10c#Stage 10b|10b]]\n| [[Narbonne]] to [[B\u00e9ziers]] || {{convert|27|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Time Trial.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || [[Individual time trial]] || {{flagathlete|[[Maurice Archambaud]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1939 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 10c#Stage 10c|10c]]\n| [[B\u00e9ziers]] to [[Montpellier]] || {{convert|70|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Maurice Archambaud]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1939 Tour de France, Stage 11 to Stage 18b#Stage 11|11]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |22 July|| [[Montpellier]] to [[Marseille]] || {{convert|212|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Fabien Galateau]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1939 Tour de France, Stage 11 to Stage 18b#Stage 12a|12a]]\n|rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\" |23 July|| [[Marseille]] to [[Saint-Rapha\u00ebl, Var|Saint-Rapha\u00ebl]] || {{convert|157|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Fran\u00e7ois Neuens]]|LUX}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1939 Tour de France, Stage 11 to Stage 18b#Stage 12b|12b]]\n| [[Saint-Rapha\u00ebl, Var|Saint-Rapha\u00ebl]] to [[Monaco]] || {{convert|122|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Maurice Archambaud]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1939 Tour de France, Stage 11 to Stage 18b#Stage 13|13]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |24 July|| [[Monaco]] to Monaco || {{convert|101|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s) || {{flagathlete|[[Pierre Gallien]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1939 Tour de France, Stage 11 to Stage 18b#Stage 14|14]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |25 July|| [[Monaco]] to [[Digne]] || {{convert|175|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Pierre Cloarec]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1939 Tour de France, Stage 11 to Stage 18b#Stage 15|15]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |26 July|| [[Digne]] to [[Brian\u00e7on]] || {{convert|219|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s) || {{flagathlete|[[Sylv\u00e8re Maes]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1939 Tour de France, Stage 11 to Stage 18b#Stage 16a|16a]]\n|rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\" |27 July|| [[Brian\u00e7on]] to Brian\u00e7on || {{convert|126|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s) || {{flagathlete|[[Pierre Jaminet]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1939 Tour de France, Stage 11 to Stage 18b#Stage 16b|16b]]\n| [[Bonneval-sur-Arc|Bonneval]] to [[Bourg-Saint-Maurice]] || {{convert|64|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountain Time Trial Stage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || [[Individual time trial|Mountain time trial]] || {{flagathlete|[[Sylv\u00e8re Maes]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1939 Tour de France, Stage 11 to Stage 18b#Stage 16c|16c]]\n| [[Bourg-Saint-Maurice]] to [[Annecy]] || {{convert|104|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Antoon van Schendel]]|NED}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 28 July\n| colspan=\"2\" | [[Annecy]]\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" | Rest day\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1939 Tour de France, Stage 11 to Stage 18b#Stage 17a|17a]]\n|rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\" |29 July|| [[Annecy]] to [[Dole, Jura|D\u00f4le]] || {{convert|226|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s) || {{flagathlete|[[Fran\u00e7ois Neuens]]|LUX}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1939 Tour de France, Stage 11 to Stage 18b#Stage 17b|17b]]\n| [[D\u00f4le]] to [[Dijon]] || {{convert|59|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Time Trial.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || [[Individual time trial]] || {{flagathlete|[[Maurice Archambaud]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1939 Tour de France, Stage 11 to Stage 18b#Stage 18a|18a]]\n|rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\" |30 July|| [[Dijon]] to [[Troyes]] || {{convert|151|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Le Grev\u00e8s]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1939 Tour de France, Stage 11 to Stage 18b#Stage 18b|18b]]\n| [[Troyes]] to [[Paris]] || {{convert|201|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Marcel Kint]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| Total\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center\"| {{convert|4224|km|0|abbr=on}}{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=108}}\n|}\n\n==Race overview==\n{{main|1939 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 10c|1939 Tour de France, Stage 11 to Stage 18b}}\n[[File:Sylv\u00e8re Maes (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|[[Sylv\u00e8re Maes]] ''(pictured at the [[1936 Tour de France|Tour 1936]])'', winner of the [[General classification in the Tour de France|general classification]]]]\nIn the first stage, regional [[Amed\u00e9e Fournier]] won the sprint of a group of nine cyclists, and was the first cyclist in 1939 to wear the yellow jersey. In the next stage, [[Romain Maes]], who had finished in the same group as Fournier, won the time trial, and captured the lead. He lost it in the second part of that stage, when a group got away.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=144\u2013147}} Three regional riders were now on top of the general classification, led by [[Jean Fontenay]].\n\n[[Ren\u00e9 Vietto]], leader of the regional South-East team, was in second place. In the fourth stage, Vietto got into the winning break, and took over the lead, closesly followed by [[Mathias Clemens]] on six seconds.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=144\u2013147}}\n\nIn the ninth stage, the single Pyrenees stage of 1939, [[Edward Vissers]] attacked instead of helping his team leader [[Sylv\u00e8re Maes]]. Vissers won the stage, but Vietto was able to stay with Maes. Maes climbed to the second place in the general classification, three minutes behind Vietto.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=144\u2013147}}\n\nMaes was able to win back a little time, and just before the Alps were climbed from stage 15 on, Vietto was still leading, with Maes still in second place, two minutes behind. Sylv\u00e8re Maes attacked on that stage, and Vietto was not able to follow. Vietto finished 17 minutes behind Maes, and lost the lead. The next stage was split in three split stages. In the first part, Vietto was able to stay close to Maes, but in the second part, the individual mountain time trial, Maes won ten minutes on Vietto. Maes was now leading with a margin of 27 minutes, and the victory seemed secure.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=144\u2013147}}\n\nIn the last stages, Maes was able to extend his lead with a few more minutes. Maes became the winner, with a margin of more than half an hour.\n\n==Classification leadership and minor prizes==\n\nThe time that each cyclist required to finish each stage was recorded, and these times were added together for the [[general classification in the Tour de France|general classification]]. If a cyclist had received a time bonus, it was subtracted from this total; all time penalties were added to this total. The cyclist with the least accumulated time was the race leader, identified by the yellow jersey. Of the 79 cyclists that started the race, 49 finished.\n\nFor the [[Mountains classification in the Tour de France|mountains classification]], 10 mountains were selected by the Tour organisation.<ref name=\"mdc1939\"/> The mountains classification in 1939 was won by [[Sylv\u00e8re Maes]]. The first cyclist to reach the top received 10 points, the second cyclist 9 points, and so on until the tenth cyclist who received 1 point.\n\nThe [[Team classification in the Tour de France|team classification]] was calculated in 1939 by adding up the times of the best three cyclists of a team; the team with the least time was the winner. In 1939, there were ten teams of eight cyclists. There were the national teams of Belgium, Switzerland, Luxembourg, Netherlands, and France. Belgium also sent a second team, \"Belgium B\". Finally, there were four regional French teams: North-East, West, South-West and South-East.<ref name=\"mdc1939\"/> The South-West team was registered with eight cyclist, but only seven cyclists started the race. Only two of the South-West cyclists finished the race, so they were not in the team classification.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:smaller; clear:both;\"\n|+Classification leadership by stage<ref name=\"tdf-statistics\">{{cite web|last=van den Akker|first=Pieter|title=Informatie over de Tour de France van 1939|trans-title=Information about the Tour de France from 1939|url=http://www.tourdefrancestatistieken.nl/tour.php?jaar=1939|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190302050021/http://www.tourdefrancestatistieken.nl/tour.php?jaar=1939|archivedate=2 March 2019|language=Dutch|website=TourDeFranceStatistieken.nl|accessdate=2 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:1%;\"| Stage\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:24%;\"| Winner\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:24%;\"| [[General classification in the Tour de France|General classification]]<br />[[File:Jersey yellow.svg|25px|link=]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:24%;\"| [[Mountains classification in the Tour de France|Mountains classification]]{{efn|name=mountains-jersey|No jersey was awarded to the leader of the mountains classification until a white jersey with red [[polka dot]]s was introduced in [[1975 Tour de France|1975]].{{sfn|Nauright|Parrish|2012|p=454}}}}\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:24%;\"| [[Team 