align:right;\" | + 3h 35' 53\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 46\n| {{flagathlete|[[Janus Hellemons]]|NED}}||Netherlands || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 3h 44' 16\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 47\n| {{flagathlete|[[Am\u00e9d\u00e9e Fournier]]|FRA}}||Ile de France/North East || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 4h 01' 56\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 48\n| {{flagathlete|[[Joseph Soffietti]]|FRA}}||South-East || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 4h 18' 46\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 49\n| {{flagathlete|[[Armand Le Moal]]|FRA}}||West || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 4h 26' 39\"\n|}\n\n===Mountains classification===\n\n{{columns-start}}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Mountains in the mountains classification<ref name=\"mdc1939\"/>{{sfn|Augendre|2016|pp=175\u2013192}}\n|-\n!Stage!! scope=\"col\" | Rider!!Height!!Mountain range!! scope=\"col\" | Winner\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 9\n|Aubisque||{{convert|1709|m|ft}}||Pyrenees||Edward Vissers\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 9\n|Tourmalet||{{convert|2115|m|ft}}||Pyrenees||Edward Vissers\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 9\n|Aspin||{{convert|1489|m|ft}}||Pyrenees||Edward Vissers\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 13\n|Braus||{{convert|1002|m|ft}}||Alps-Maritimes||Sylv\u00e8re Maes\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 15\n|Allos||{{convert|2250|m|ft}}||Alps||Edward Vissers\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 15\n|Vars||{{convert|2110|m|ft}}||Alps||Edward Vissers\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 15\n|Izoard||{{convert|2361|m|ft}}||Alps||Sylv\u00e8re Maes\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 16a\n|Galibier||{{convert|2556|m|ft}}||Alps||Dante Gianello\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 16\n|Iseran||{{convert|2770|m|ft}}||Alps||Sylv\u00e8re Maes\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 17a\n|Faucille||{{convert|1320|m|ft}}||Alps||Sylv\u00e8re Maes\n|}\n\n{{column}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Final mountains classification (1\u20135)<ref name=\"mdc1939\"/><ref name=\"tgv\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tour-giro-vuelta.net/|title=Tour-Giro-Vuelta|accessdate=14 October 2009|author=Van Lonkhuyzen, Michiel}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Rank!! scope=\"col\" | Rider!! scope=\"col\" | Team!! scope=\"col\" | Points\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |1\n| {{flagathlete|[[Sylv\u00e8re Maes]]|BEL}}||Belgium|| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 86\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |2\n| {{flagathlete|[[Edward Vissers]]|BEL}}||Belgium|| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 84\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |3\n| {{flagathlete|[[Albert Ritseveldt]]|BEL}}||Belgium B|| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 71\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |4\n| {{flagathlete|[[Dante Gianello]]|FRA}}||France|| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 61\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |5\n| {{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Vietto]]|FRA}} ||South-East|| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 22\n|}\n\n{{columns-end}}\n\n===Team classification===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Final team classification (1\u20139)<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/><ref name=\"lc\">{{cite news|url=http://www.archiefleeuwardercourant.nl/site/article.do?code=LC&date=19390731&id=LC-19390731-11007|title=De Ronde van Frankrijk \u2013 Sylver Maes winnaar|date=31 July 1939|accessdate=14 October 2009|publisher=Leeuwarder Courant|language=Dutch}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Rank!! scope=\"col\" | Team!! scope=\"col\" | Time\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |1\n| Belgium B || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 398h 17' 20\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |2\n| France || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 35' 47\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |3\n| Belgium || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 36' 18\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |4\n| Luxembourg || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 1h 12' 35\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |5\n| France North-East || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 1h 23' 20\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |6\n| France South-East || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 1h 38' 09\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |7\n| Netherlands || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 2h 06' 07\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |8\n| France West || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 5h 50' 37\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |9\n| Switzerland || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 6h 45' 27\"\n|}\n\n==Aftermath==\nAlthough he did not win the race, Ren\u00e9 Vietto became a popular cyclist. He was the most popular runner-up in France until [[Raymond Poulidor]].<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/>\n\nThe sales of the organising newspaper ''[[l'Auto]]'' had dropped to 164000, and the newspaper was sold to [[Raymond Paten\u00f4tre]].{{sfn|Thompson|2008|p=310}} A few months after Germany had conquered France in the Second World War, Paten\u00f4tre sold l'Auto to the Germans.{{sfn|Thompson|2008|p=35}}\n\nDirectly after the Tour, the organisation announced the 1940 Tour de France would be run in 20 stages and five rest days.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://emeroteca.coni.it/?q=node/6&f=3804&p=1|title=Novita per l'edizione 1940|work=Il littoriale|publisher=Biblioteca digitale|language=Italian|date=31 July 1939|accessdate=11 February 2010}}</ref> But the Second World War made it impossible to hold a Tour de France in the next years, although [[Tour de France during the Second World War|some replacing races]] were held. Only in 1947 would the Tour be held again, and Vietto would again play an important role then, holding the yellow jersey as leader of the general classification for 15 of the 21 stages.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://veloarchive.com/races/tour/1947.php|title=1947: Robic snatches it at the death|author=James, Tom|date=15 August 2003|accessdate=25 January 2010|publisher=VeloArchive}}</ref>\n\nThe victory of Maes would be the last Belgian Tour victory for 30 years, until [[Eddy Merckx]] won the [[1969 Tour de France]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.standaard.be/artikel/detail.aspx?artikelid=DMF20090721_001|title=21 juli 1969. Eddy Merckx wint zijn eerste Tour|date=21 July 2009|publisher=De Standaard|language=Dutch|accessdate=25 January 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book|first=Jacques|last=Augendre|author-link=Jacques Augendre|url=http://netstorage.lequipe.fr/ASO/cyclisme/le-tour/2016/histoire/TDF16_GH_Interactif-PROD.pdf|title=Guide historique|trans-title=Historical guide|year=2016|language=French|access-date=27 October 2016|format=PDF|work=[[Tour de France]]|location=Paris|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817121602/http://netstorage.lequipe.fr/ASO/cyclisme/le-tour/2016/histoire/TDF16_GH_Interactif-PROD.pdf|archive-date=17 August 2016|url-status=live|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Bowen|first=Wayne H|url=https://archive.org/details/spainduringworld00bowe_0|url-access=registration|title=Spain During World War II|location=Columbia, MO|publisher=[[University of Missouri Press]]|year=2006|isbn=978-0-8262-1658-8|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=McGann|first1=Bill|last2=McGann|first2=Carol|title=The Story of the Tour de France: 1903\u20131964|volume=1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jxq20JskqMUC|publisher=Dog Ear Publishing|location=Indianapolis, IN|year=2006|isbn=978-1-59858-180-5|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Nauright|first1=John|last2=Parrish|first2=Charles|title=Sports Around the World: History, Culture, and Practice|volume=2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IkLYDgTnMxEC|year=2012|publisher=[[ABC-CLIO]]|location=Santa Barbara, CA|isbn=978-1-59884-300-2|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Thompson|first=Christopher S.|title=The Tour de France: A Cultural History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UpzzPqexF00C|publisher=[[University of California Press]]|location=Oakland, CA|year=2008|isbn=978-0-520-25630-9|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline|Tour de France 1939|1939 Tour de France}}\n\n{{Cycling stage recaps|1939 Tour de France|1|10c|11|18b}}\n{{Tour de France}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1939 Tour De France}}\n[[Category:1939 Tour de France| ]]\n[[Category:1939 in road cycling|Tour de France]]\n[[Category:Tour de France by year]]\n[[Category:July 1939 sports events|Tour de France]]\n", "name_user": "BaldBoris", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eInnovations and changes:Changes from the previous Tour \u2192 Innovations and changes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1939_Tour_de_France"}
{"title_page": "David Montgomery (baseball)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{short description|American baseball executive}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = David Montgomery\n| image = David Montgomery.jpg\n| alt =\n| caption = Montgomery in 2011\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1946|06|26}}\n| birth_place = [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|2019|05|08|1946|06|26}}\n| nationality = [[United States of America|United States]]\n| other_names =\n| known_for = President and CEO of the [[Philadelphia Phillies]]\n| occupation = [[Baseball]] executive\n}}\n\n'''David Paul Montgomery''' (June 26, 1946{{Citation needed|date=April 2019}} \u2013 May 8, 2019) was an American businessman and baseball executive. He served as chairman, minority-owner,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Salisbury|first1=Jim|title=No longer a team owner, Bill Giles still has Phillies opinions|url=https://www.nbcsports.com/philadelphia/philadelphia-phillies/no-longer-team-owner-bill-giles-still-has-phillies-opinions|publisher=NBC Sports|date=July 14, 2015|accessdate=July 14, 2015}}</ref> and president of the [[Philadelphia Phillies]] of [[Major League Baseball]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/team/front_office.jsp?c_id=phi|title=Front Office Directory|publisher=Philadelphia Phillies|accessdate=August 19, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070219055701/http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/team/front_office.jsp?c_id=phi|archive-date=February 19, 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Phillies Announce David Montgomery is Out as President|url=https://philadelphia.cbslocal.com/2015/01/28/phillies-announce-david-montgomery-is-out-as-president/|publisher=CBS Local Media|date=January 28, 2015|accessdate=July 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nAs a child growing up in [[Philadelphia]], Montgomery attended [[Philadelphia Phillies]] games at [[Shibe Park|Connie Mack Stadium]]. Before attending college, Montgomery worked as a paper delivery boy and a high school baseball coach.<ref name=\"upenn\"/> Montgomery was a 1964 alumnus of the [[William Penn Charter School]] in Philadelphia<ref>{{cite news|title=David Montgomery |url=http://www.bloomberglink.com/people/david-montgomery/ |accessdate=July 14, 2013 |newspaper=Bloomberg Link |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140102192848/http://www.bloomberglink.com/people/david-montgomery/ |archivedate=January 2, 2014 }}</ref> and as an [[Undergraduate education|undergraduate]] attended the [[University of Pennsylvania]] where he was first a [[Liberal arts education|liberal arts]] major,<ref name=\"upenn\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thedp.com/article/2002/10/phillies_ceo_gives_life_lesson|title=Phillies CEO gives life lesson|last=Silverman|first=Rachel|date=October 2, 2002|work=The Daily Pennsylvanian|accessdate=April 22, 2010}}</ref> and then a history major.<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/10/22/sports/baseball/22baseball.html|title=Phillies\u2019 President Took Path From Upper Deck to the Owner's Box|last=Kepner|first=Tyler|date=October 22, 2008|newspaper=The New York Times|page=B12|accessdate=April 22, 2010}}</ref> Montgomery was a member of [[Phi Sigma Kappa]] fraternity while an undergraduate. Montgomery continued to attend Phillies games as a college student with future governor [[Ed Rendell]], where he recalled \"<nowiki>[trying]</nowiki> to eat all the food that $5 could buy... as they shared their thoughts with the players\".<ref name=\"nytimes\"/> He also attended the [[Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania|Wharton Business School]] as a graduate student, graduating in 1970.<ref name=\"wharton\">{{cite web|url=http://www.whartonjournal.com/2.10095/batting-practice-in-huntsman-david-montgomery-wg-70-1.1456172 |title=Batting practice in Huntsman: David Montgomery WG'70 |date=February 17, 2003 |work=The Wharton Journal |accessdate=April 22, 2010 |first=David |last=Capece |first2=Dana |last2=Berneman |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718035019/http://www.whartonjournal.com/2.10095/batting-practice-in-huntsman-david-montgomery-wg-70-1.1456172 |archivedate=July 18, 2011 }}</ref> During his tenure at Wharton, he also coached the [[Lineman (American football)|linemen]] for the varsity [[American football|football]] team at [[Germantown Academy]].<ref name=\"nytimes\"/>\n\n==Baseball career==\nAfter interviewing for positions with the [[Scott Paper Company]] and [[Quaker Oats Company|Quaker Oats]] and being encouraged by Rendell to apply for a job with the [[Philadelphia 76ers]], Montgomery reached out to former Phillies ace [[Robin Roberts (baseball)|Robin Roberts]], whose son he coached at Germantown, about a job with the baseball club.<ref name=\"nytimes\"/> Montgomery was hired as a member of the Phillies' sales department in 1971,<ref name=\"wharton\"/> becoming director of sales and marketing in the mid-1970s and the head of the business department by 1980.<ref name=\"nytimes\"/> During the early 1970s, he was also the team's scoreboard operator.<ref name=\"nytimes\"/>\n\nMontgomery, along with co-owner [[Bill Giles (baseball)|Bill Giles]], purchased the team in 1981 for $30,000,000 (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|30000000|1981|r=-6}}}} today);<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/finance/lists/33/2005/LIR.jhtml?passListId=33&passYear=2005&passListType=Misc&uniqueId=335119&datatype=Misc|title=MLB Team Valuations 2005|last=Ozanian|first=Michael K., ed|date=April 7, 2005|publisher=Forbes|accessdate=August 19, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050410131632/http://www.forbes.com/finance/lists/33/2005/LIR.jhtml?passListId=33&passYear=2005&passListType=Misc&uniqueId=335119&datatype=Misc|archive-date=April 10, 2005|url-status=dead}}</ref> Giles, the primary owner, named Montgomery the executive vice president of the team.<ref name=\"nytimes\"/> In 1997, when Giles left the team presidency to become the chairman and focus on negotiating for a new stadium for the team,<ref>{{cite book|last=Jordan|first=David M.|title=Occasional glory: the history of the Philadelphia Phillies|publisher=McFarland|year=2012|page=182|isbn=9781476600543|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fIO9bQOyt48C&pg=PA182|edition=2nd}}</ref> he recommended Montgomery to replace him as team president.<ref name=\"nytimes\"/> In so doing, Montgomery became the first native of Philadelphia to run the club in over 60 years.<ref>{{cite book|last=Westcott|first=Rich|title=Philadelphia Phillies Past & Present|publisher=MBI Publishing Company|year=2010|page=36|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=K_e8KWxmo_kC&pg=PA36&dq=david+montgomery+phillies&hl=en&ei=cmDPS7vuDYOKlweF6MmgCw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3&ved=0CEEQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=david%20montgomery%20phillies&f=false|isbn=0-7603-3784-5}}</ref> One of his focuses with the team was brand development, evidenced by the team's commitment to signing successful players to long-term contracts prior to the opening of [[Citizens Bank Park]] in 2004.<ref name=\"nytimes\"/><ref name=\"wharton\"/>\n\nIn August 2014, Montgomery took a leave of absence from the Phillies, while undergoing treatment for jaw bone cancer. When he returned to the team in January 2015, he assumed the title of chairman, while Giles became chairman emeritus. [[Pat Gillick]], who served as interim president during Montgomery's leave, assumed the role permanently.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.phillies.mlb.com/news/article/107718484/david-montgomery-returns-to-phillies-as-chairman|title=Montgomery Returns to Phillies as Chairman|last=Zolecki|first=Todd|date=January 28, 2015|publisher=MLB.com|accessdate=February 3, 2015}}{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, the Phillies opened a $4 million facility at their [[Carpenter Complex]] as the first indoor climate-controlled training center at a major-league spring-training site. It is used by the team year-round in Clearwater for training, rehabilitation, and daily workouts. On March 22, 2018, the Phillies renamed the indoor facility at the complex the \"David P. Montgomery Baseball Performance Center.\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Matt|last=Breen |title=Phillies name Clearwater facility after David Montgomery |url=http://www.philly.com/philly/sports/phillies/phillies-front-office-spring-training-david-montgomery-20180322.html|work=philly.com|date=March 22, 2018|accessdate=March 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Outside baseball==\nMontgomery was a trustee of the University of Pennsylvania, served community action groups, and was a member of Major League Baseball Enterprise's board of directors.<ref name=\"upenn\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nMontgomery and his wife Lyn had three children and three grandchildren. Montgomery was diagnosed with cancer of the jawbone in May 2014, and underwent surgery in that same year.<ref>[https://6abc.com/sports/phillies-chairman-montgomery-72-dies-of-cancer/5290544/]</ref> He died from the disease on the morning of May 8, 2019, at the age of 72.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://philadelphia.cbslocal.com/2019/05/08/phillies-chairman-david-montgomery-passes-away-at-72-after-5-year-battle-with-cancer/ |title=Philadelphia Phillies Chairman David Montgomery Passes Away At 72 After 5-Year Battle With Cancer \u2013 CBS Philly |publisher=Philadelphia.cbslocal.com |date= |accessdate=May 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/team/front_office.jsp?c_id=phi Philadelphia Phillies Front Office]\n*[http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com Official team site]\n\n{{Philadelphia Phillies}}\n{{Philadelphia Phillies owners}}\n{{Philadelphia Phillies Presidents}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Montgomery, David}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball team presidents]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia Phillies executives]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia Phillies owners]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball executives]]\n[[Category:Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania alumni]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:William Penn Charter School alumni]]\n[[Category:Deaths from bone cancer]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{short description|American baseball executive}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = David Montgomery\n| image = David Montgomery.jpg\n| alt =\n| caption = Montgomery in 2011\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1946|06|26}}\n| birth_place = [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|2019|05|08|1946|06|26}}\n| nationality = [[United States of America|United States]]\n| other_names =\n| known_for = President and CEO of the [[Philadelphia Phillies]]\n| occupation = [[Baseball]] executive\n}}\n\n'''David Paul Montgomery''' (June 26, 1946{{Citation needed|date=April 2019}} \u2013 May 8, 2019) was an American businessman and baseball executive. He served as chairman, minority-owner,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Salisbury|first1=Jim|title=No longer a team owner, Bill Giles still has Phillies opinions|url=https://www.nbcsports.com/philadelphia/philadelphia-phillies/no-longer-team-owner-bill-giles-still-has-phillies-opinions|publisher=NBC Sports|date=July 14, 2015|accessdate=July 14, 2015}}</ref> and president of the [[Philadelphia Phillies]] of [[Major League Baseball]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/team/front_office.jsp?c_id=phi|title=Front Office Directory|publisher=Philadelphia Phillies|accessdate=August 19, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070219055701/http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/team/front_office.jsp?c_id=phi|archive-date=February 19, 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Phillies Announce David Montgomery is Out as President|url=https://philadelphia.cbslocal.com/2015/01/28/phillies-announce-david-montgomery-is-out-as-president/|publisher=CBS Local Media|date=January 28, 2015|accessdate=July 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nAs a child growing up in [[Philadelphia]], Montgomery attended [[Philadelphia Phillies]] games at [[Shibe Park|Connie Mack Stadium]]. Before attending college, Montgomery worked as a paper delivery boy and a high school baseball coach.<ref name=\"upenn\"/> Montgomery was a 1964 alumnus of the [[William Penn Charter School]] in Philadelphia<ref>{{cite news|title=David Montgomery |url=http://www.bloomberglink.com/people/david-montgomery/ |accessdate=July 14, 2013 |newspaper=Bloomberg Link |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140102192848/http://www.bloomberglink.com/people/david-montgomery/ |archivedate=January 2, 2014 }}</ref> and as an [[Undergraduate education|undergraduate]] attended the [[University of Pennsylvania]] where he was first a [[Liberal arts education|liberal arts]] major,<ref name=\"upenn\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thedp.com/article/2002/10/phillies_ceo_gives_life_lesson|title=Phillies CEO gives life lesson|last=Silverman|first=Rachel|date=October 2, 2002|work=The Daily Pennsylvanian|accessdate=April 22, 2010}}</ref> and then a history major.<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/10/22/sports/baseball/22baseball.html|title=Phillies\u2019 President Took Path From Upper Deck to the Owner's Box|last=Kepner|first=Tyler|date=October 22, 2008|newspaper=The New York Times|page=B12|accessdate=April 22, 2010}}</ref> Montgomery was a member of [[Phi Sigma Kappa]] fraternity while an undergraduate. Montgomery continued to attend Phillies games as a college student with future governor [[Ed Rendell]], where he recalled \"<nowiki>[trying]</nowiki> to eat all the food that $5 could buy... as they shared their thoughts with the players\".<ref name=\"nytimes\"/> He also attended the [[Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania|Wharton Business School]] as a graduate student, graduating in 1970.<ref name=\"wharton\">{{cite web|url=http://www.whartonjournal.com/2.10095/batting-practice-in-huntsman-david-montgomery-wg-70-1.1456172 |title=Batting practice in Huntsman: David Montgomery WG'70 |date=February 17, 2003 |work=The Wharton Journal |accessdate=April 22, 2010 |first=David |last=Capece |first2=Dana |last2=Berneman |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718035019/http://www.whartonjournal.com/2.10095/batting-practice-in-huntsman-david-montgomery-wg-70-1.1456172 |archivedate=July 18, 2011 }}</ref> During his tenure at Wharton, he also coached the [[Lineman (American football)|linemen]] for the varsity [[American football|football]] team at [[Germantown Academy]].<ref name=\"nytimes\"/>\n\n==Baseball career==\nAfter interviewing for positions with the [[Scott Paper Company]] and [[Quaker Oats Company|Quaker Oats]] and being encouraged by Rendell to apply for a job with the [[Philadelphia 76ers]], Montgomery reached out to former Phillies ace [[Robin Roberts (baseball)|Robin Roberts]], whose son he coached at Germantown, about a job with the baseball club.<ref name=\"nytimes\"/> Montgomery was hired as a member of the Phillies' sales department in 1971,<ref name=\"wharton\"/> becoming director of sales and marketing in the mid-1970s and the head of the business department by 1980.<ref name=\"nytimes\"/> During the early 1970s, he was also the team's scoreboard operator.<ref name=\"nytimes\"/>\n\nMontgomery, along with co-owner [[Bill Giles (baseball)|Bill Giles]], purchased the team in 1981 for $30,000,000 (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|30000000|1981|r=-6}}}} today);<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/finance/lists/33/2005/LIR.jhtml?passListId=33&passYear=2005&passListType=Misc&uniqueId=335119&datatype=Misc|title=MLB Team Valuations 2005|last=Ozanian|first=Michael K., ed|date=April 7, 2005|publisher=Forbes|accessdate=August 19, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050410131632/http://www.forbes.com/finance/lists/33/2005/LIR.jhtml?passListId=33&passYear=2005&passListType=Misc&uniqueId=335119&datatype=Misc|archive-date=April 10, 2005|url-status=dead}}</ref> Giles, the primary owner, named Montgomery the executive vice president of the team.<ref name=\"nytimes\"/> In 1997, when Giles left the team presidency to become the chairman and focus on negotiating for a new stadium for the team,<ref>{{cite book|last=Jordan|first=David M.|title=Occasional glory: the history of the Philadelphia Phillies|publisher=McFarland|year=2012|page=182|isbn=9781476600543|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fIO9bQOyt48C&pg=PA182|edition=2nd}}</ref> he recommended Montgomery to replace him as team president.<ref name=\"nytimes\"/> In so doing, Montgomery became the first native of Philadelphia to run the club in over 60 years.<ref>{{cite book|last=Westcott|first=Rich|title=Philadelphia Phillies Past & Present|publisher=MBI Publishing Company|year=2010|page=36|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=K_e8KWxmo_kC&pg=PA36&dq=david+montgomery+phillies&hl=en&ei=cmDPS7vuDYOKlweF6MmgCw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3&ved=0CEEQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=david%20montgomery%20phillies&f=false|isbn=0-7603-3784-5}}</ref> One of his focuses with the team was brand development, evidenced by the team's commitment to signing successful players to long-term contracts prior to the opening of [[Citizens Bank Park]] in 2004.<ref name=\"nytimes\"/><ref name=\"wharton\"/>\n\nIn August 2014, Montgomery took a leave of absence from the Phillies, while undergoing treatment for jaw bone cancer. When he returned to the team in January 2015, he assumed the title of chairman, while Giles became chairman emeritus. [[Pat Gillick]], who served as interim president during Montgomery's leave, assumed the role permanently.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.phillies.mlb.com/news/article/107718484/david-montgomery-returns-to-phillies-as-chairman|title=Montgomery Returns to Phillies as Chairman|last=Zolecki|first=Todd|date=January 28, 2015|publisher=MLB.com|accessdate=February 3, 2015}}{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, the Phillies opened a $4 million facility at their [[Carpenter Complex]] as the first indoor climate-controlled training center at a major-league spring-training site. It is used by the team year-round in Clearwater for training, rehabilitation, and daily workouts. On March 22, 2018, the Phillies renamed the indoor facility at the complex the \"David P. Montgomery Baseball Performance Center.\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Matt|last=Breen |title=Phillies name Clearwater facility after David Montgomery |url=http://www.philly.com/philly/sports/phillies/phillies-front-office-spring-training-david-montgomery-20180322.html|work=philly.com|date=March 22, 2018|accessdate=March 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Outside baseball==\nMontgomery was a trustee of the University of Pennsylvania, served community action groups, and was a member of Major League Baseball Enterprise's board of directors.<ref name=\"upenn\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nMontgomery and his wife Lyn had three children and three grandchildren. Montgomery was diagnosed with cancer of the jawbone in May 2014, and underwent surgery in that same year.<ref>[https://6abc.com/sports/phillies-chairman-montgomery-72-dies-of-cancer/5290544/]</ref> He died from the disease on the morning of May 8, 2019 at the age of 72.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://philadelphia.cbslocal.com/2019/05/08/phillies-chairman-david-montgomery-passes-away-at-72-after-5-year-battle-with-cancer/ |title=Philadelphia Phillies Chairman David Montgomery Passes Away At 72 After 5-Year Battle With Cancer \u2013 CBS Philly |publisher=Philadelphia.cbslocal.com |date= |accessdate=May 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/team/front_office.jsp?c_id=phi Philadelphia Phillies Front Office]\n*[http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com Official team site]\n\n{{Philadelphia Phillies}}\n{{Philadelphia Phillies owners}}\n{{Philadelphia Phillies Presidents}}\n\n{{